WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.800
So Shiny for Python, if you're not already familiar with Shiny, Shiny is a framework

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:18.719
for building interactive web applications. So it's been almost 10 years to the date that

00:00:18.719 --> 00:00:26.040
we've had Shiny in R. But over the past year or so, we've been working on essentially porting

00:00:26.040 --> 00:00:33.080
that foundation over to Python so that, you know, Python users can have a similar, very

00:00:33.080 --> 00:00:39.959
approachable framework for building interactive web applications without needing to already

00:00:39.959 --> 00:00:45.880
know HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. So even though we try to make this approachable, we still

00:00:45.880 --> 00:00:52.240
sort of build this on a foundation that's very flexible and scalable. So these are kind

00:00:52.240 --> 00:01:00.680
of built on foundations that allow you to, you know, build out your own custom components,

00:01:00.680 --> 00:01:07.680
sort of extend some of the reactivity concepts to, you know, implement your own sort of modular,

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:15.699
you know, functionalities. And also, you know, the sort of reactive framework that powers

00:01:15.699 --> 00:01:23.500
all of this. One of the reasons why it's so nice is it kind of allows you to declare,

00:01:23.500 --> 00:01:28.540
you know, what should happen. And then Shiny handles the details of, you know, what actual

00:01:28.540 --> 00:01:35.699
computations to execute when they need to be executed. So it kind of allows you to write

00:01:35.699 --> 00:01:40.900
this expressive reactive code without needing to handle like every specific case of when

00:01:40.900 --> 00:01:47.660
this changes, then also update this other thing. So for a very sort of hello world example,

00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:55.019
you can see it here running in the browser. And this is how you would start programming

00:01:55.019 --> 00:02:03.459
a very basic Shiny application. So you can see I'm importing from Shiny, there's a UI

00:02:03.459 --> 00:02:10.880
package inside of Shiny. So this is how you'll actually create or define where things should

00:02:10.880 --> 00:02:17.839
go in the actual user interface of the Shiny application. There's also a rendering package.

00:02:17.839 --> 00:02:27.600
And this is sort of utilities for rendering things like matplotlib plots or various different

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:35.039
types of Python output into actual stuff that can go into a user interface. And then every

00:02:35.039 --> 00:02:41.880
Shiny application is going to want this capital A app to actually bring the two main pieces

00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:48.440
of the Shiny app together, that being the user interface here from lines three to six.

00:02:48.440 --> 00:02:54.839
This is the definition of what you see on the right here, as well as the server logic,

00:02:54.839 --> 00:03:02.639
which kind of takes Python objects and renders them into things that can go into the user

00:03:03.320 --> 00:03:14.199
interface. So in this particular basic example, I have created this user interface by first

00:03:14.199 --> 00:03:20.160
creating sort of like a page container. So we have several different variants on different

00:03:20.160 --> 00:03:25.800
types of pages that you can create. Page fluid in a lot of cases is, you know, it's pretty

00:03:25.839 --> 00:03:34.160
basic, but covers most use cases for just starting a new user interface. And then inside

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:42.360
of there, I will put a slider components and give this an ID of lowercase n. And then this

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:48.119
is a label that should appear just above the slider. So I'm going to put a capital N for

00:03:48.119 --> 00:03:53.720
label, define the minimum and the maximum for the slider, and then a starting value for

00:03:53.720 --> 00:04:01.039
that slider. And the way that Shiny works is, you know, you basically in this user interface,

00:04:01.039 --> 00:04:08.559
you give every kind of user interface component an ID, and then you can reference whatever

00:04:08.559 --> 00:04:16.359
the current value of that input is on the server by saying input dot n, and then you

00:04:16.359 --> 00:04:24.239
kind of read that value by calling it like a function. So if I had several different

00:04:24.239 --> 00:04:30.040
input components with different IDs, I would, you know, of course, change the name here

00:04:30.040 --> 00:04:35.160
after the dots and then call it like a function to basically read whatever the current value

00:04:35.160 --> 00:04:44.380
is. And you might have noticed in this server definition, when you define this server function,

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:51.619
it takes three arguments, the input values that are coming in from this user interface,

00:04:51.619 --> 00:05:03.420
the output argument, and we're going to use this output object to basically hook up values

00:05:03.420 --> 00:05:10.339
that we create on the server up with the user interface. And then also a session which we're

00:05:10.339 --> 00:05:17.019
not going to get into here, but this can allow you to do things specific to a specific

00:05:17.019 --> 00:05:25.019
user's session experience. All right, so with this server definition, I'm going to create

00:05:25.019 --> 00:05:34.579
an output that's going to be connected to this output text verbatim with an ID of text.

00:05:34.579 --> 00:05:42.220
And with every output, when you first create it, you're going to want to then provide a

00:05:42.220 --> 00:05:50.820
rendering decorator. So here, the at render dot text basically means I want to define

00:05:50.820 --> 00:05:58.980
a function that's going to return a string that I can just put verbatim into this whatever

00:05:58.980 --> 00:06:05.779
UI component I'm hooking up this return value to. And this part right here, the actual name

00:06:05.779 --> 00:06:11.859
of this function that I'm providing to the render text and the output decorator is going

00:06:11.859 --> 00:06:20.579
to define the output ID essentially that should match this sort of UI container that I want

00:06:20.579 --> 00:06:26.380
to hook up this value to. Now that I've kind of declared that there's an output that I

00:06:26.380 --> 00:06:33.660
want to render as text with an ID of text or TXT and provide it inside of and provide

00:06:33.660 --> 00:06:42.339
this sort of function expression that reads a reactive value, this input dot n. By declaring

00:06:42.339 --> 00:06:49.619
it this way, then Shiny knows basically whenever this input n changes, I will re-execute this

00:06:49.619 --> 00:06:58.299
function and basically create a new return value for this text verbatim here. So that's

00:06:58.299 --> 00:07:06.500
a long way of saying like whenever I change this slider value here, this gray text box

00:07:06.500 --> 00:07:12.059
below is going to update to be two times whatever the value of this slider is. A neat thing

00:07:12.059 --> 00:07:18.160
about this that I don't really want to steal my colleague Winston's thunder too much on

00:07:18.160 --> 00:07:24.720
is the fact that this is all running in the browser. So we've kind of built this foundation

00:07:24.720 --> 00:07:32.079
for allowing you to take, you know, simple Shiny applications and run them purely in

00:07:32.079 --> 00:07:37.339
the browser without a Python process running in the background. So this is actually statically

00:07:37.339 --> 00:07:44.320
hosted on Netlify through GitHub pages. And I have a running Shiny application here that

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:50.679
I can actually modify the source code of this Shiny application and say, I want maybe

00:07:50.679 --> 00:07:57.200
five times the current value of this slider. Restart. It's going to start with an initial

00:07:57.200 --> 00:08:04.040
value of 40 here, and now I've got five times 40 in the output. So that's just kind of a

00:08:04.040 --> 00:08:08.600
neat side note that you'll notice as I'm kind of going through more examples. Some of these

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:14.200
will just run purely in the browser, but you could learn more about that in another

00:08:14.200 --> 00:08:20.160
video. Currently, I don't know if this link will change at any point. I would imagine

00:08:20.160 --> 00:08:27.480
that it will eventually have the company's branding and everything in the link name.

00:08:27.480 --> 00:08:33.599
But for now, yes, pyshiny.netlify.app is the best place to go to. And then there's kind

00:08:33.599 --> 00:08:40.840
of some getting started stuff, some information on how to install, information about how to

00:08:40.840 --> 00:08:47.919
deploy to our different like professional products, going into some concepts in depth.

00:08:47.919 --> 00:08:55.799
And then there's a link here to examples that is kind of a different site with all sorts

00:08:55.799 --> 00:08:59.400
of different examples that are running in the browser.

